DMA
DMA (Direct Memory Access) is a method that allows I/O devices to transfer data directly to and from main memory without involving the CPU.<SEP>DMA refers to Direct Memory Access, a method that allows hardware components to directly access system memory without CPU intervention during data transfers.

Cycle Stealing
Cycle Stealing is a DMA technique where the I/O device temporarily takes over a memory cycle to transfer data, prioritizing I/O operations.

I/O Device
I/O device refers to any peripheral device that communicates with the computer system by sending or receiving data.<SEP>An I/O device is a peripheral component that communicates with the CPU and may generate interrupt requests when ready.<SEP>I/O device refers to peripheral equipment used for input and output operations that communicate with the CPU through interrupt requests.<SEP>The I/O device is a hardware component responsible for preparing data for input or output and signaling the DMA controller when ready.

CPU
CPU, the Central Processing Unit, is the primary processing component of a computer system, serving as the core of its architectural design. It is responsible for executing instructions fetched from memory, performing arithmetic and logical operations through its Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU), and managing the flow of data across system components. The CPU oversees all system operations, coordinating tasks between software applications and hardware elements, and plays a central role in managing input/output (I/O) processes by issuing commands and reading status signals through the I/O interface. It is tasked with handling interrupt requests, detecting signals from peripheral devices and system events, and managing the interruption of program execution to address urgent tasks such as hardware signals or time-sensitive operations. This includes executing interrupt service programs and responding to external stimuli in a timely and efficient manner. Additionally, the CPU manages DMA (Direct Memory Access) operations by initializing the DMA controller and temporarily relinquishing control of the system bus to allow the DMA controller to handle data transfers independently, thereby improving system efficiency. After data transfer completion, the CPU performs post-processing tasks to ensure data integrity and operational continuity. Consistently described as the central component driving computation and system coordination, the CPU integrates instruction execution, data management, interrupt handling, and I/O control, establishing its fundamental role in the functionality and performance of computing systems.<SEP>CPU is the central processing unit, which is bypassed during data transfers in DMA mode to reduce processing overhead.<SEP>CPU is the central processing unit responsible for executing initialization programs, issuing commands, and querying device status during I/O operations.

Alternate CPU and DMA Access
Alternate CPU and DMA Access is a DMA method that divides the CPUâ€™s work cycle into two parts, one dedicated to CPU access and another to DMA access.

Main Memory
Main memory is the primary storage component in a computer system used for storing data and instructions.<SEP>Main memory stores data and instructions currently in use by the CPU.<SEP>Main memory is a primary storage component where data is temporarily held during processing and I/O operations.<SEP>Main memory is a component of the computer system that stores data and is accessible by both the CPU and external devices.

Memory Access Conflict
Memory Access Conflict occurs when both the CPU and I/O device attempt to access main memory simultaneously, potentially causing data integrity issues.

Stop CPU Access
Stop CPU Access is a DMA strategy where the CPU halts its access to main memory during DMA data transfer.

Data Transfer Rate
Data Transfer Rate refers to the speed at which data is moved between devices and memory, a critical factor for high-performance I/O operations.

Bus Control
Bus Control refers to the management of access to the system bus, especially in scenarios involving multiple devices competing for access.

Memory Cycle
Memory Cycle is the time required to complete a single memory access operation, essential for timing in DMA operations.

Control Line
The Control Line transmits read/write signals, interrupt requests and responses, arbitration signals, and handshake signals.

Control Register
The Control Register holds control information from the CPU intended for external devices.

Data Line
The Data Line transmits read/write data, status information, control signals, and interrupt type codes between the CPU and I/O interface.

I/O Control Logic
The I/O Control Logic interprets commands from the control register and manages data flow and signal transmission to external devices.

Status Register
The Status Register records the operational status information of the I/O interface and connected devices.<SEP>The status register in the I/O interface holds readiness and operational status information reported by the peripheral device, which is then forwarded to the CPU.

I/O Interface
The I/O Interface is a hardware component that manages data transfer between the CPU and peripheral devices.<SEP>I/O Interface is a hardware component that facilitates communication between a computer and external devices, with various types based on data transfer methods, control strategies, and programmability.<SEP>I/O Interface, also known as I/O controller, serves as the interface between the host system and peripheral devices, enabling information exchange and resolving differences in working methods, data formats, and speeds.

Address Line
The Address Line carries the address of the register within the I/O interface that is to be accessed.

Data Buffer Register
The Data Buffer Register is used to temporarily store data being transferred between the CPU or memory and the I/O interface.<SEP>Data buffer register, also known as data port, is a hardware component in the I/O interface used to temporarily hold data during transfer.

I/O Instruction
I/O Instructions are specialized commands used to access I/O registers and are restricted to use in operating system kernel-level I/O software.<SEP>I/O instructions are machine-level commands used by the CPU to communicate and exchange data with I/O devices.

Privilege Instruction
A Privilege Instruction is a type of instruction that can only be executed in privileged mode, such as in the operating system kernel, and includes I/O instructions.

Peripheral Device
A Peripheral Device is an external hardware component connected to the computer system via the I/O interface for input/output operations.

Disable Interrupts
Disabling interrupts ensures that no higher-priority interrupts interfere during the protection of the program's breakpoint and context.

PSW
The PSW (Program Status Word) is a register that contains status and control flags used by the CPU during program execution.

Program Counter
The Program Counter is a register that holds the address of the next instruction to be executed.<SEP>The program counter is a register in the CPU that holds the address of the next instruction to be executed, which is updated during interrupt processing.

Interrupt Service Program
The interrupt service program is a sequence of instructions executed by the CPU in response to an interrupt signal.<SEP>The interrupt service program is the software component responsible for executing specific tasks in response to an interrupt, located after the interrupt addressing phase.<SEP>The interrupt service program is a specific routine executed by the CPU in response to a valid interrupt request.<SEP>The interrupt service program is a software routine executed by the CPU in response to an interrupt signal from an I/O device.<SEP>Interrupt service program is a segment of code executed by the CPU in response to an interrupt request to handle data transfer or system events.<SEP>The interrupt service program is the code executed by the CPU in response to an interrupt request.

Save Breakpoint
Saving the breakpoint involves storing the address of the next instruction to be executed, ensuring the program can resume correctly after the interrupt service routine.<SEP>Saving the breakpoint records the exact location in the program where execution was interrupted, allowing for correct resumption afterward.

Interrupt Response Process
The interrupt response process is a sequence of hardware-implemented operations that occur when a CPU responds to an interrupt, including disabling interrupts, saving the program breakpoint, and initiating the interrupt service routine.

Interrupt Implicit Instruction
The interrupt implicit instruction refers to a series of automatic hardware operations performed during interrupt handling, not a formal instruction in the instruction set but a conceptual description of hardware actions.<SEP>The interrupt implicit instruction is a hardware mechanism that performs the initial steps of interrupt handling, including disabling interrupts and saving the breakpoint.

Vector Interrupt
The vector interrupt method uses hardware-generated vectors to identify and directly route to the appropriate interrupt service routine.<SEP>A vector interrupt is a type of interrupt where the CPU uses a predefined interrupt vector to directly locate the service routineâ€™s entry address, enabling faster response.

Interrupt Handling
Interrupt handling is the process by which the CPU manages external or internal interrupt signals and executes the appropriate response.<SEP>Interrupt handling is the process by which a CPU responds to and manages interrupt requests from various sources.<SEP>Interrupt handling in DMA mode is restricted to error detection and end-of-transfer notifications, not data movement.

Stack
The stack is a data structure used by the CPU to store the program's breakpoint and context information during interrupt handling.

Re-Execute Instruction
The re-execute instruction method is used in exception handling, where the failed instruction is resumed after the exception is processed.

Breakpoint
The breakpoint is the point in the program where execution was interrupted, typically the address of the next instruction to be executed.<SEP>Breakpoint is the point in the original program where execution is suspended during an interrupt and will resume afterward.

Hardware Vector Method
The hardware vector method is a technique for identifying the source of an interrupt using hardware logic to generate the service routine address.

Interrupt Source
The interrupt source refers to the origin of an interrupt signal, such as I/O devices or internal events.<SEP>An interrupt source is a device or event that generates an interrupt request to the CPU, with multiple sources possible in a computer system.<SEP>The interrupt source is any device or condition that generates a request for the CPU to pause current tasks and handle a higher-priority event.

Software Query Method
The software query method determines the interrupt source by executing a software routine to poll the interrupt status.

Specific Register
A specific register is a dedicated hardware register used by the CPU to store the program's breakpoint and context when the stack is unavailable or not used.

Save Context and Mask Word
Saving context and mask word preserves the state of the CPUâ€™s working registers and interrupt mask level to prevent corruption during interrupt processing.

Interrupt Service Program Addressing
Interrupt service program addressing determines the starting address of the interrupt service routine, handled by hardware via the interrupt implicit instruction.

Context Information
Context information refers to the values in user-visible work registers at the time of interruption, which must be preserved for proper restoration.

Interrupt Handling Process
The interrupt handling process is a sequence of steps executed by a computer system to manage and respond to interrupt signals, ensuring system stability and task continuity.

Disabling Interrupts
Disabling interrupts is the first step in the interrupt handling process, preventing further interrupts from being processed during critical operations.

Breakpoint Information
Breakpoint information is the program counter value at the moment of interruption, automatically saved by hardware during interrupt response.

Enabling Interrupts
Enabling interrupts allows higher-priority interrupt requests to be handled, supporting interrupt nesting.

Recovery Context and Mask Word
Recovery context and mask word restores the CPUâ€™s register state and interrupt mask to their pre-interrupt levels.

Single-Level Interrupt
A single-level interrupt is a type of interrupt handling where interrupt nesting is disabled, omitting steps 5 and 7 from the full sequence.

Execute Interrupt Service Program
Executing the interrupt service program is the primary purpose of an interrupt, performing necessary tasks to handle the event.

Hardware-Implemented Steps
Hardware-implemented steps are performed automatically by the CPU, including disabling interrupts, saving the breakpoint, and interrupt addressing.

Interrupt Return
Interrupt return is the final step in the process, returning control to the original program at the saved breakpoint.

Software-Implemented Steps
Software-implemented steps are executed by the interrupt service program, including saving context, enabling interrupts, and recovery actions.

Interrupt Request
An interrupt request is a signal sent by a device or event to request the CPU's attention, occurring at random times.<SEP>An interrupt request is a signal sent to the CPU indicating that an external event requires immediate attention.<SEP>Interrupt request is a signal sent by an external device to the CPU to request immediate attention for processing.<SEP>An interrupt request is a signal sent by the DMA controller to the CPU to indicate that data transfer is complete and post-processing is needed.

Maskable Interrupt
An interrupt that can be disabled by the CPU through disabling interrupts; it has the lowest priority and is not processed when the CPU is in an interrupt-disabled state.<SEP>A maskable interrupt is a type of interrupt that can be disabled or blocked by the CPU and has lower priority than non-maskable interrupts.

Interrupt Request Marking Register
A register composed of multiple interrupt request marking flip-flops used to store the state of all interrupt sources, either centralized in the CPU or distributed across sources.

INTR Line
A signal line used to transmit maskable interrupts to the CPU.

Interrupt Request Marking Flip-Flop
A flip-flop used to record interrupt events and distinguish between different interrupt sources; when set to "1", it indicates a pending interrupt request.

Non-Maskable Interrupt
An interrupt that cannot be disabled by the CPU; used for critical and urgent events such as power failure or clock ticks, and has the highest priority.<SEP>A non-maskable interrupt is a type of interrupt that cannot be ignored by the CPU and has the highest priority in the interrupt response hierarchy.

NMI Line
A signal line used to transmit non-maskable interrupts to the CPU, which are not blocked by interrupt disable states.

Clock Interrupt
A type of non-maskable interrupt used to manage timekeeping and system timing functions.

Power Failure
A critical system event that triggers a non-maskable interrupt to initiate emergency response procedures.

Data Bus
The data bus carries the actual data being transferred between components such as CPU, memory, and I/O devices.

Control Bus
The control bus carries signals that coordinate and regulate operations between system components.

Single Bus Structure
The single bus structure connects the CPU, main memory, and I/O devices through a single shared bus, allowing direct communication between devices without intermediate intervention.

Dual Bus Structure
The dual bus structure employs two independent buses: a memory bus for CPU and main memory communication, and an I/O bus for external device communication, reducing contention on the main data path.

Address Bus
The address bus transmits memory addresses from the CPU to main memory and I/O devices.

I/O Bus
The I/O bus enables communication between the CPU and various peripheral devices.<SEP>The I/O bus is a communication pathway that connects I/O hardware components to the host computer system.

Three Bus Structure
The three bus structure uses three independent buses-main memory bus, I/O bus, and DMA bus-to enable parallel data transfers between CPU, memory, peripherals, and high-speed devices.

Main Memory Bus
The main memory bus facilitates data exchange between the CPU and main memory.

DMA Bus
The DMA bus allows direct data transfer between main memory and high-speed peripheral devices without CPU involvement.

I/O Devices
I/O devices are external hardware components that communicate with the computer system for input and output operations.<SEP>I/O devices are external components used for input and output operations, ranging from low to high data transfer rates.

Concurrency
Concurrency refers to the ability of a system to perform multiple operations simultaneously; single bus structures do not support this.

Channel
A channel is a hardware component used in dual and triple bus architectures to manage data transfers between the CPU, memory, and I/O devices.

System Bus
The system bus is the central communication pathway linking the main components of a computer system.<SEP>The system bus is the communication pathway connecting various components of a computer system, supporting data, address, and control signals.<SEP>The system bus is the communication pathway that allows data transfer between components, which the DMA controller accesses via a bus request during data transfer.<SEP>A system bus is a type of computer bus that connects the CPU to main components of the computer, such as memory and I/O controllers.

High-Speed Peripheral
High-speed peripherals are devices that require rapid data transfer rates, often connected via dedicated DMA buses.

Bandwidth
Bandwidth refers to the data transfer capacity of a bus; single bus structures have low bandwidth due to shared usage.<SEP>Bandwidth is the maximum rate of data transfer across a bus, measured in bits per second, indicating performance capability.

Load
Load describes the amount of data traffic on a bus; single bus structures suffer from high load due to shared access.

Performance
Performance measures how efficiently a system handles operations; three bus structures improve performance by enabling faster responses.

Data Transfer
Data transfer is the movement of information between system components via buses.<SEP>Data transfer refers to the process of moving data between devices over a bus, which is regulated by timing methods.<SEP>Data transfer refers to the process of moving information between two or more devices on a bus during a single bus cycle.<SEP>Data transfer is the movement of information between the host system and external devices, facilitated by interrupt mechanisms.<SEP>Data transfer is the core phase where the DMA controller manages the transfer of data blocks using hardware-level loops, without CPU involvement.<SEP>Data transfer is the movement of data between the CPU and an external device, typically occurring only when the device is ready.

Throughput
Throughput refers to the amount of data processed over time; three bus structures improve system throughput.

Multi-Device Communication
In single bus structures, multiple devices must compete for access to the single bus, limiting parallel data exchange.

System Clock Frequency
The system clock frequency determines the timing speed of operations in a system and limits how fast data transfers can occur.

Clock Signal
A clock signal is a periodic electronic signal used in synchronous timing to regulate data transfer cycles on a bus.<SEP>The clock signal defines timing intervals in a synchronous system, used for sampling signals such as Wait.

Data Ready Condition
The data ready condition refers to the state where data has been prepared and is available for retrieval.

Master Device
The master device is responsible for initiating data transfer by sending addresses and commands on the bus.<SEP>A master device is a system component that initiates data transfer requests on a bus and controls the communication sequence.<SEP>A master device is an initiator on the bus, such as a CPU or DMA, that requests and controls data transfer.

Semi-Synchronous Bus
The semi-synchronous bus is a type of bus system that operates based on a clock signal and uses the Wait signal to determine data readiness.

Wait Response Signal Line
The Wait response signal line is used in a semi-synchronous bus system to indicate whether data is ready for transfer.

Total System Speed
Total system speed refers to the overall performance of a system under different timing methods.

Slave Device
The slave device is selected by the master device and responds to requests by preparing or transmitting data.<SEP>A slave device is a system component that responds to requests from a master device and performs data transfer upon instruction.<SEP>A slave device is a target on the bus, responding to access requests from a master device during data transfer.

Bus Transaction
A bus transaction involves the complete process of a data transfer, from initiation to completion.<SEP>A bus transaction is a sequence of operations from requesting bus access to completing bus usage, occurring within a single bus cycle.

Separated Timing Method
The separated timing method divides a bus transaction into two distinct phases: request and response, improving bus utilization.

Bus Usage
Bus usage refers to the allocation and control of the bus during data transfer operations.

Device A
Device A refers to a master device that initiates a bus transaction by sending requests.

Single Direction Information Flow
Single direction information flow refers to the unidirectional data and control transmission during each phase of the separated timing method.

Response Phase
The response phase is the second stage where the slave device prepares and sends the requested data after obtaining bus access.

Request Phase
The request phase is the first stage of the separated timing method where the master device sends commands and addresses.<SEP>The request phase is when a master device (CPU or DMA) issues a bus transfer request and acquires bus control.

Bus Access Release
Bus access release occurs when a device releases the bus after completing its transmission to allow other devices to use it.

Device B
Device B refers to a slave device that responds to a request by preparing and sending data.

Separated Timing
Separated timing is a bus timing method characterized by decoupled command and data phases, enabling independent timing for each component.

Bus Cycle
A bus cycle is a time interval during which data transfer occurs between sender and receiver, defined by a clocking mechanism or handshake.<SEP>A bus cycle refers to the time period in which a series of activities related to bus transactions takes place.

Idle Wait Time
Idle wait time is the period during which the bus remains unused while a slave device prepares data, representing inefficiency in traditional timing methods.

Asynchronous Timing
Asynchronous timing relies on handshake signals between sender and receiver without a shared clock, allowing variable bus cycle lengths and compatibility with devices of differing speeds.

Synchronous Timing
Synchronous timing uses a unified clock signal to coordinate data transfer between sender and receiver, with fixed bus cycles and consistent timing for all devices.

Half-Synchronous Timing
Half-synchronous timing combines synchronous signal timing with asynchronous Wait signal handling, allowing slower devices to synchronize through a Wait response line.

Bus Timing
Bus timing refers to the time coordination required during data exchange on a bus, governed by protocols or rules, including synchronous, asynchronous, half-synchronous, and separated types.

Handshake Signal
A handshake signal is a control signal exchanged between devices during asynchronous timing to coordinate data transfer.

Request Signal
A request signal is sent by a master device to initiate data exchange, used in asynchronous timing modes.

Data Bit
Data bits are the primary bits carrying information in serial communication, transmitted one at a time.

Start Bit
A start bit is a signal used in asynchronous serial communication to indicate the beginning of a data character.

Parity Bit
A parity bit is an optional bit used in asynchronous serial communication for basic error detection.

Stop Bit
A stop bit is a signal used in asynchronous serial communication to mark the end of a data character.

Wait Signal
A Wait signal is an additional line used in half-synchronous timing to indicate whether data is ready for transfer.

Synchronous Serial Communication
Synchronous serial communication involves bit-by-bit transmission where the receiver is synchronized with the senderâ€™s clock, using start and end markers only at block boundaries.

Response Signal
A response signal is sent by a slave device to acknowledge a request signal, used in asynchronous timing.

Asynchronous Serial Communication
Asynchronous serial communication uses start and stop bits for each character, allowing independent timing between sender and receiver.

System Clock
A system clock is a centralized timing source used in synchronous systems to coordinate operations across all connected devices.

Bus Cycle Length
Bus cycle length is the duration of a single cycle in bus timing, which can be fixed in synchronous systems or variable in asynchronous systems.

Interface
An interface is a logical component that coordinates data transfer between external devices and the host, handling speed matching, signal level conversion, and data format alignment.

I/O Software
I/O software includes drivers, user programs, management software, and patches, enabling command processing and communication between CPU and I/O devices.

External Storage Device
External storage devices are secondary storage units beyond main memory and CPU cache, such as hard disks and optical discs.

Input Device
An input device is a hardware component used to enter commands, text, and data into a computer system, such as a keyboard or mouse.<SEP>An input device is a hardware component that sends data to the CPU and generates interrupts during data transfer.

External Device
External devices include input/output devices and external storage devices that connect via I/O interfaces.<SEP>External device is a hardware component that performs input/output tasks and can send an interrupt signal upon completion of a task.

Host Computer
The host computer is the central system that receives input from external devices and sends output to them.

Input/Output System
The Input/Output System manages the transfer of information between external devices and the host computer, handling control of data input and output processes.<SEP>The Input/Output System is the overall framework responsible for managing data transfer between the CPU, main memory, and external I/O devices.

Output Device
An output device is a hardware component that transfers information from the computer system to external environment for display or exchange, such as a monitor or printer.<SEP>An output device is a hardware component that receives data from the CPU and generates interrupts upon completion of data transfer.

I/O Hardware
I/O hardware comprises external devices, device controllers, I/O interfaces, and I/O buses, forming the physical infrastructure for data transfer.

Device Controller
A device controller manages the operational actions of individual I/O devices through control signals and data handling.

Channel Instruction
Channel instructions are specialized commands that support data transfer between the CPU and I/O devices via dedicated channels.

Interrupt Response Timing
Interrupt response timing is the point at which the CPU checks for interrupt requests, occurring at the end of each instruction cycle.

Instruction Execution
Instruction execution refers to the process of completing a single CPU instruction, which determines the timing of interrupt sampling.

System Control
System control refers to the set of conditions and state flags (e.g., interrupt enable) that govern whether the CPU responds to interrupts.

Interrupt Enable Flag
The interrupt enable flag is a status bit in the CPU that determines whether interrupts are allowed to be processed.

I/O Interrupt
I/O interrupt refers to an interrupt generated by an input/output device to signal readiness or completion of a task, and is subject to CPU response timing at the end of instruction execution.

Exception
An exception is a type of interrupt that is not subject to the standard interrupt response rules, typically triggered by internal errors or urgent conditions.

Instruction Completion
Instruction completion marks the end of a single instruction cycle, which is the moment when the CPU checks for interrupt signals.

Nonmaskable Interrupt
A nonmaskable interrupt is a high-priority interrupt that cannot be blocked by the interrupt disable state and must be processed immediately.

Interrupt Query Program
An interrupt query program is a software routine used to determine the order of interrupt responses when multiple requests are present.

I/O Transfer Interrupt
I/O transfer interrupts are generated during input/output operations and are prioritized based on device speed and function.

Hardware Queue
A hardware queue is a physical component used in interrupt handling to manage and prioritize incoming interrupt requests.

Interrupt Response Priority
Interrupt response priority refers to the order in which a CPU responds to interrupt requests, determined by hardware logic or query programs when multiple interrupts occur simultaneously.

Low-Speed Device
A low-speed device is an input/output device that generates interrupts requiring less urgent attention compared to high-speed devices.

High-Speed Device
A high-speed device is an input/output device that generates interrupts requiring rapid response due to its fast data transfer rate.

Normal Device
A normal device is a hardware component with standard interrupt handling requirements, without time-critical constraints.

Multiple Interrupts
Multiple interrupts refer to the scenario where more than one interrupt request occurs simultaneously, requiring a structured response mechanism.

Interrupt Masking
Interrupt masking is a technique used to dynamically control which interrupts are allowed to be processed, enabling adjustment of processing priority.

Real-Time Device
A real-time device is a hardware component that requires immediate processing of interrupt requests due to time-sensitive operations.

Program Query Method
The program query method involves the CPU continuously checking the status of I/O devices to determine if they are ready for data transfer.<SEP>Program query method is an I/O control technique where CPU directly executes programs to manage data exchange, involving status checking and data transfer cycles.

Program Interrupt Method
The program interrupt method allows the CPU to respond only when an I/O device sends an interrupt request, indicating readiness for data transfer.

Channel Method
The channel method uses a channel control unit to manage I/O operations; the host initiates the operation, and the channel executes the channel program to complete data transfer.

DMA Method
The DMA method enables direct data transfer between main memory and I/O devices without CPU intervention, using a dedicated data path.

Channel Control Unit
The channel control unit is a hardware component that manages I/O operations, connecting the host to multiple peripheral devices.

High Data Transfer Rate Devices
High data transfer rate devices are peripherals requiring fast data movement and are typically managed using DMA or channel methods.

Channel Program
The channel program is a sequence of instructions executed by the channel control unit to perform a specified I/O operation.

Low Data Transfer Rate Devices
Low data transfer rate devices are external peripherals that operate at a slower data exchange pace and are typically controlled via program query or interrupt methods.

USB
USB is a common I/O bus standard used for connecting low-speed peripheral devices to a computer system.<SEP>USB, or Universal Serial Bus, is a widely used I/O bus for connecting external devices, supporting plug-and-play and hot-swapping capabilities with strong connectivity.

PCI
PCI is a common I/O bus standard widely used for connecting expansion cards and peripherals in computer systems.<SEP>PCI, or Peripheral Component Interconnect, is a high-performance 32-bit or 64-bit bus used for connecting peripherals such as graphics cards, sound cards, and network cards. DMA Interface
DMA Interface enables direct memory access, allowing data to be transferred between memory and devices without CPU involvement, improving efficiency.

Interrupt Interface
Interrupt Interface allows a device to signal the CPU when it is ready, enabling the CPU to perform other tasks while waiting.

Programmable Interface
Programmable Interface allows its functionality to be altered through software configuration, enabling flexible system adaptation.

Parallel Interface
Parallel Interface transfers data in chunks where all bits of a byte or word are sent simultaneously, requiring more wires and supports higher data throughput.

Non-Programmable Interface
Non-Programmable Interface has fixed functionality determined by its hardware design and cannot be altered via software.

Serial Interface
Serial Interface transmits data one bit at a time in sequence, using fewer wires and suitable for long-distance communication.

Program Query Interface
Program Query Interface involves the CPU repeatedly checking the status of an I/O device until it is ready, leading to inefficient CPU utilization.

Data Format Conversion
Data Format Conversion is a function performed by the I/O interface to adapt data between the host system and external devices.

Transfer Phase
The transfer phase is when data exchange occurs between the master and slave modules, which can be unidirectional or bidirectional.

Release Phase
The release phase is when the master device removes its information from the system bus, relinquishing bus ownership.

Arbitration Phase
The arbitration phase is when the bus arbiter determines which requester will be granted bus access for the next transfer cycle.

Non-Burst Transfer Mode
Non-burst transfer mode involves sending address followed by data in each cycle, with typically only one word-length data transfer per cycle.

Addressing Phase
The addressing phase is when the master device sends the address of the target slave device and associated commands via the bus to initiate the slave module.

Burst Transfer Mode
Burst transfer mode enables continuous, grouped data transfers; the initial address is sent, followed by multiple consecutive data units without releasing the bus until the entire group is transferred.

Bus Arbiter
A bus arbiter is a component responsible for resolving competing requests and assigning the next bus access to a requesting entity.

Clock Cycle
A clock cycle is a single unit of time in which digital circuits perform operations, such as data transfer, synchronized by a clock signal.

Signal Format Conversion
Signal format conversion allows the I/O interface to adapt between different electrical levels, data formats, and coding schemes (e.g., parallel/serial, analog/digital).

Address Decoding
Address decoding is the process by which the I/O interface interprets address codes from the CPU to select the appropriate peripheral device for communication.

Data Buffering
Data buffering involves the use of temporary storage (data buffer registers) to bridge speed differences between the CPU and peripheral devices, preventing data loss.

Communication Coordination
Communication coordination enables the I/O interface to manage timing and synchronization between the host and peripherals of differing speeds.

Host System
The host system refers to the central computing unit that communicates with peripheral devices through the I/O interface.

Command and Status Transfer
Command and status transfer involves the exchange of control commands and status information between the CPU, I/O interface, and peripheral devices through command and status registers.

Peripheral Devices
Peripheral devices are external components that connect to the host system, exhibiting diverse working characteristics and requirements.<SEP>Peripheral devices include high-speed hardware such as disk drives, graphics cards, sound cards, and network cards, which transfer large volumes of data using DMA.

Command Register
The command register within the I/O interface receives and stores control commands sent by the CPU to initiate or control peripheral device operations.

Interrupt Masking Technology
Interrupt masking technology enables dynamic adjustment of interrupt handling priorities by using a mask register to selectively block or allow interrupt requests.

Interrupt Priority
Interrupt priority denotes the actual handling order of multiple interrupts, which can be dynamically adjusted using interrupt masking techniques.

Single Interrupt
Single interrupt occurs when a CPU does not respond to a new interrupt request with higher priority while executing an interrupt service program.

Interrupt Request Signal
The interrupt request signal (IRi) is the signal sent by device i to request an interrupt, recorded in the interrupt request register.

Multilevel Interrupt
Multilevel interrupt refers to the ability of a CPU to suspend a current interrupt service routine to handle a higher-priority interrupt, also known as interrupt nesting.

Interrupt Mask Word
The interrupt mask word is the content of the interrupt mask word register, used to control whether a specific interrupt source is allowed or masked.

Interrupt Mask Word Register
The interrupt mask word register is a hardware component that stores the interrupt mask word, where each bit corresponds to a specific interrupt source.

Interrupt Request Register
The interrupt request register records the interrupt requests from various devices, with each bit corresponding to a specific interrupt source.

Program Interrupt
Program interrupt is a mechanism in computing where the CPU temporarily halts the current program to handle urgent exceptions or special requests, then resumes the original program from the breakpoint.

Ready Queue
Ready queue is a list of processes awaiting CPU execution, from which the CPU selects the next process to run.

Interrupt Arbitration Circuit
The interrupt arbitration circuit evaluates and determines which interrupt should be serviced based on fixed response priority.

Response Priority
Response priority refers to the fixed priority order used by the interrupt arbitration circuit to determine which interrupt is processed first if multiple interrupts are not masked.

Multitasking
Multitasking refers to the ability of a system to execute multiple processes concurrently using interrupts for switching between tasks.

Device I
Device I is a hardware component that generates an interrupt request signal (IRi) when an event occurs.

Real-Time Processing
Real-time processing is a system capability that requires rapid response to events, enabled through interrupt systems.

Multi-Processor System
Multi-processor system is a computing environment with multiple processors that use interrupts for inter-processor communication and task switching.

Soft Interrupt
Soft interrupt is a mechanism used for switching between user applications and operating system routines, also known as a software interrupt.

Current Process
Current process is the program currently being executed by the CPU before an interrupt occurs.

User Intervention
User intervention is the act of a human operator influencing system execution, which relies on the interrupt system for processing.

Software Error
Software error refers to unexpected or erroneous behavior in a program that triggers an interrupt for handling.

Supervisor Mode
Supervisor mode is a privileged execution state of the CPU used by the operating system for handling critical tasks, including interrupts.

Operating System
Operating System is the system software that manages hardware and software resources and includes the supervisor mode for handling interrupts.

Hardware Fault
Hardware fault is a type of abnormal condition that requires immediate CPU intervention and is handled through the interrupt system.

Inter-Processor Communication
In a multi-processor system, processors communicate and switch tasks using interrupt systems.

DMA Controller
The DMA controller is a hardware component that manages the data transfer process independently, issuing requests and handling interrupts.

Preprocessing
Preprocessing is the initial phase of the DMA data transfer process where the CPU initializes the DMA controller, sets transfer direction, and tests and starts the I/O device.

Post-Processing
Post-processing is the final stage where the DMA controller issues an interrupt to the CPU, which then handles completion tasks such as data verification and error diagnosis.

Data Transfer Process
The data transfer process in DMA is divided into three stages: preprocessing, data transfer, and post-processing.

Data Block
A data block is the fundamental unit of data transfer in DMA, processed as a single entity during the data transfer phase.<SEP>Data block refers to a sequence of data transferred in a single operation during DMA.

Bus Request
A bus request is a signal sent by the DMA controller to the CPU to gain control of the system bus for data transfer.

Data Port
Data Port is a type of I/O port that allows the CPU to perform read and write operations on data.

Status Port
Status Port is a type of I/O port that enables the CPU to read the current status of external devices.

Port Addressing
Port Addressing refers to the process of assigning a unique address to each I/O port so that the CPU can access it.

I/O Mapping
I/O Mapping is another term for Independent Addressing, where I/O ports are given a separate address space from main memory.

Independent Addressing
Independent Addressing, also known as I/O Mapping, is a method where I/O ports are separately addressed from the main memory space, using distinct address spaces.

I/O Port
I/O Port refers to a register within an I/O interface circuit that can be directly accessed by the CPU, including data ports, status ports, and control ports.

Control Port
Control Port is a type of I/O port used by the CPU to write control commands to external devices.

Unified Addressing
Unified Addressing, also known as Memory Mapping, is a method where I/O ports are assigned addresses within the main memory space, sharing the same address space.

I/O Instructions
I/O Instructions are specialized CPU instructions used to access I/O ports in systems with independent addressing.

I/O Address Space
I/O Address Space is the address range reserved for I/O ports, distinct in independent addressing.

Memory Access Instructions
Memory Access Instructions are standard CPU instructions used to access both memory and I/O ports in unified addressing systems.

Memory Mapping
Memory Mapping is another term for Unified Addressing, where I/O ports are integrated into the main memory address space.

Main Memory Address Space
Main Memory Address Space refers to the range of addresses used for storing data and instructions in the primary memory.

Keyboard
The keyboard is the most commonly used input device for issuing commands or entering data into a computer.

Mouse
The mouse is a common pointing input device that links user actions to positions on the computer screen.

Printer
The printer is an output device that produces physical copies of digital data on various media.

Display Monitor
The display monitor is an output device that displays visual information using a matrix of pixels, categorized by display technology.

Dot Matrix Printer
The dot matrix printer is a type of printer capable of multi-layer carbon copying and prints using a series of pins.

LED Display
The LED display is a type of flat-panel monitor using light-emitting diodes for backlighting or pixel illumination.

CRT Display
The CRT display is a type of monitor that uses a cathode ray tube to generate images.

LCD Display
The LCD display is a flat-panel monitor that uses liquid crystal technology to produce images.

Inkjet Printer
The inkjet printer uses droplets of ink sprayed through nozzles to create images or text, particularly suited for high-quality color printing.

Laser Printer
The laser printer uses laser beams and electrostatic processes to produce high-quality, fast prints and combines laser and electronic imaging technologies.

Magnetic Drum
The magnetic drum is a cylindrical storage device with magnetic coating used for data storage, primarily in early computing systems.

Tape Storage
Tape storage is a magnetic surface storage method that uses magnetic tape to store data sequentially.

Disk Storage
Disk storage is a type of magnetic surface storage that uses rotating disks to store data magnetically.

Magnetic Surface Storage
Magnetic surface storage refers to storage devices where magnetic materials are coated on metal or plastic substrates to store data.

Solid-State Drive
The solid-state drive (SSD) is a storage device that uses Flash memory to store data without moving parts, providing faster performance.

Flash Memory
Flash memory is a type of non-volatile storage used in SSDs and other electronic devices for high-speed data storage.

Optical Disc Storage
Optical disc storage is a non-contact storage system that records and reads data using focused laser beams on optical media.

Optical Disc
The optical disc is a storage medium that uses laser technology to write and read data, such as CDs, DVDs, and Blu-ray discs.

Grayscale Level
Grayscale level refers to the number of brightness or color variations a display can show; higher levels yield more detailed and realistic images.

Optical Disc Controller
The optical disc controller manages data transfer and operation between the optical disc drive and the computer system.

Refresh Rate
Refresh rate is the number of times per second a display updates its image, measured in Hz, with higher rates reducing flicker.

Refresh
Refresh is the process of redrawing the image on a screen before the previous image fades, maintaining a stable display.

Optical Disc Drive
The optical disc drive is the hardware component used to read from and write to optical discs.

Screen Size
Screen size refers to the diagonal length of a displayâ€™s screen, measured in inches, commonly ranging from 12 to 32 inches.

Resolution
Resolution is the number of pixels displayed on a screen, expressed as width Ã— height (e.g., 800Ã—600, 1280Ã—1024).

Video RAM
Video RAM (VRAM) is a type of memory used to store image data temporarily for quick access during screen refresh.

Binary Information
Binary information refers to digital data represented in bits (0s and 1s), processed by computers.

Laser Beam
A laser beam is a focused, coherent stream of light used in optical disc drives and laser printers for precise data recording.

Sensing Drum
The sensing drum, also known as a photoconductive drum, is a key component in laser printers that holds an electrostatic image before transferring it to paper.

Toner
Toner is a powder used in laser printers to form text and images by adhering to charged areas on a drum.

Pixel
A pixel is the smallest unit of a digital image or display, represented as a single point in a raster image.

Color Mixing
Color mixing is the process of combining different colored inks or light to create a desired color, especially in inkjet printers using primary colors.

Computer
The keyboard serves as a primary input device for sending commands or data to a computer.

Storage System
Magnetic surface storage uses magnetic materials on substrates to store digital data.

Hardware Circuit
Hardware circuit is a physical component that performs tasks such as address determination and data counting during DMA transfers.

Main Memory Buffer
Main memory buffer is a dedicated area in main memory used to temporarily hold data for transfer to or from external devices.

External Devices
External devices are peripheral components that interact with the computer system for data transfer.

I/O
I/O refers to input/output operations between the computer system and external devices.

DMA Way
DMA way is a data transfer method that enables direct data communication between main memory and DMA interface without involving the CPU.<SEP>DMA way is a hardware-controlled data transfer method that enables high-speed data movement between peripheral devices and memory without CPU intervention.

Program Preprocessing
Program preprocessing is the initialization step required before starting a DMA transfer, performed via software.

Interrupt Postprocessing
Interrupt postprocessing is the step executed after DMA transfer completion, signaled through an interrupt.

System Efficiency
System efficiency refers to the improved performance and throughput achieved by parallel operation of CPU and I/O.

ISA
ISA, or Industry Standard Architecture, is an early system bus standard with low transmission speed, high CPU utilization, and high hardware interrupt resource usage. It is a parallel bus and belongs to the system bus category.

EISA
EISA, or Extended Industry Standard Architecture, is an enhanced version of ISA that supports multiple bus masters and burst transfers while maintaining full compatibility with ISA. It is a parallel system bus.

PCI-Express
PCI-Express, or PCI-E, is a high-speed serial bus that supports bidirectional and full-duplex communication, offering significantly higher bandwidth than PCI and AGP.

AGP
AGP, or Accelerated Graphics Port, is a dedicated video interface standard designed to accelerate the transfer of video and 3D graphics data between main memory and the graphics card.

VESA
VESA, or Video Electronics Standards Association, is an organization that developed the VESA local bus standard to support high-speed data transfer for multimedia applications.

VESA Local Bus
VESA Local Bus is a 32-bit local bus designed to connect high-speed peripherals like graphics cards directly to the CPU bus, improving performance over ISA.

RS-232C
RS-232C is a serial interface standard used for connecting data terminal equipment (DTE) and data communication equipment (DCE) for binary data exchange.

SCSI
SCSI, or Small Computer System Interface, is a standard interface for connecting computers to peripheral devices such as hard drives, known for its use of an independent processor.

IDE
IDE, or Integrated Drive Electronics, is a device bus standard used for connecting storage devices like hard drives and optical drives to motherboards, often referred to as ATA.

Local Bus
A local bus is a high-speed bus located between the CPU and peripheral bus (like ISA) to connect fast peripherals directly to the CPU, improving data transfer performance.

PCMCIA
PCMCIA, or Personal Computer Memory Card International Association, is a standard for expansion cards used primarily in laptops, offering plug-and-play functionality.

SATA
SATA, or Serial Advanced Technology Attachment, is a serial hardware interface standard for connecting storage devices to a motherboard, designed for high-speed data transfer.

Parallel Bus
A parallel bus transfers multiple bits simultaneously across multiple data lines, typically offering higher bandwidth but greater complexity and signal integrity challenges.

Serial Bus
A serial bus transmits data one bit at a time over a single channel, reducing cable complexity and electromagnetic interference but requiring higher clock speeds for equivalent bandwidth.

Bus Width
Bus width refers to the number of data bits that can be transferred simultaneously over a bus, directly affecting throughput capacity.

Addressing Capability
Addressing capability refers to the number of unique memory or device locations a bus can access, determined by the address bus width.

Video Electronics Standards Association
Video Electronics Standards Association is the full name of VESA, an organization that established standards for video electronic interfaces, particularly for high-speed data transfer in multimedia systems.

Hot-Swapping
Hot-swapping is the ability to connect or disconnect a device without powering down the system, often supported by modern buses like USB.

Clock Frequency
Clock frequency is the rate at which a bus operates, measured in hertz, influencing data transfer speed and synchronization.

Burst Transfer
Burst transfer enables the bus to transmit a sequence of data without requiring individual transaction control for each transfer, improving efficiency.

Plug-and-Play
Plug-and-Play is a feature that allows devices to be automatically detected, configured, and utilized by the operating system upon connection.

Peripheral Component Interconnect
Peripheral Component Interconnect is the full name of PCI, a high-performance bus standard used for connecting peripheral devices such as graphics cards, sound cards, and network cards to a computer's motherboard.

Device Bus
RS-232C is used as a device bus for serial communication between DTE and DCE.

System Performance
VESA Local Bus improves system performance by offloading high-speed peripherals from ISA.<SEP>System performance improves in DMA mode due to reduced CPU utilization during data transfers.

Data Performance
PCI-Express delivers superior data performance through high-speed serial transmission and full-duplex operation.

Graphics Performance
AGP significantly improves graphics performance by enabling direct CPU-graphics memory access.

Storage Performance
SATA offers improved storage performance over IDE through faster serial data transfer.

Hardware
Hardware refers to the physical components used to implement DMA, enabling direct data transfers without CPU involvement.

Direct Data Path
Direct data path is a dedicated channel established between peripherals and memory in DMA mode, bypassing the CPU.

Data Transfer Overhead
Data transfer overhead refers to the CPU workload during data movement; DMA reduces this by avoiding CPU involvement.

Memory
Memory is the primary storage unit that receives or sends data directly via the DMA path.

Initialization Program
Initialization program is a sequence of instructions executed by the CPU to set up transfer parameters before starting an I/O operation.

Device Status Register
Device status register, also known as status port, is a hardware component in the I/O interface that stores the current operational status of the I/O device.

I/O Operation
I/O operation refers to the process of transferring data between the CPU and an external device, involving initialization, status checking, and data exchange.

Command Word
Command word is a control instruction sent by the CPU to initiate or manage the operation of an I/O device.

Address and Counter Parameter
Address and counter parameter refers to the memory address and transfer count used to track data transfer progress during an I/O operation.

Device Readiness
Device readiness indicates the state in which the I/O device is prepared to perform a data transfer.

Timing Interval
Timing interval refers to the fixed period between consecutive status queries in a timer query method, adjusted according to device data transfer rate.

Noah Carter
Noah Carter is a sprinter who set a new 100m sprint record at the World Athletics Championship.

Tokyo
Tokyo is the host city of the World Athletics Championship.

Exclusive Query
Exclusive query is a program query method where the CPU continuously checks the device status after initiation, keeping the CPU fully occupied with I/O operations.

Timer Query
Timer query is a program query method where the CPU periodically checks the device status at set intervals, allowing the CPU to resume other tasks in between checks.

World Athletics Championship
The World Athletics Championship is a global sports competition featuring top athletes in track and field.

Interrupt Vector
An interrupt vector is the entry address of an interrupt service routine, which the CPU uses to transfer control to the appropriate handler after detecting an interrupt.

Non-Vector Interrupt
A non-vector interrupt is a type of interrupt where the CPU does not use a predefined vector to identify the interrupt service routine, requiring manual identification of the source.

Interrupt Type Number
An interrupt type number is a unique identifier assigned to each interrupt source, used by the CPU to locate the corresponding interrupt vector.

Central Processing Unit
The Central Processing Unit is the primary component of a computer that performs most processing tasks, including handling interrupts.

Interrupt Service Routine
An interrupt service routine is a specific function executed in response to an interrupt, triggered by a hardware or software event.

100m Sprint Record
The 100m sprint record is a benchmark in athletics, recently broken by Noah Carter.

Interrupt Vector Table
The interrupt vector table is a memory region that stores the entry addresses (vectors) of all interrupt service routines, organized by interrupt type number.

Carbon-Fiber Spikes
Carbon-fiber spikes are advanced sprinting shoes that provide enhanced speed and traction.

World Athletics Federation
The World Athletics Federation is the governing body overseeing the World Athletics Championship and record validations.

Interrupt Vector Method
The interrupt vector method is a technique used by the CPU to determine the entry address of an interrupt service routine by using the interrupt type number to access the interrupt vector table.
